# Project Architecture

`claude-hub` is a local-first GUI and bridge for running agent providers against user-registered projects. Cursor CLI is the preferred development tooling, but the app supports multiple runtime providers.

- Agent execution goes through `@claude-hub/agent-runner`. Do not call provider CLIs directly from server, orchestrator, trigger, or route code.
- Supported providers are `claude` and `cursor`, configured through `AppConfig.defaultProvider` and `AppConfig.providers`.
- Channels are conversational and orchestrator-mediated. v1 ships Discord DMs.
- Triggers are deterministic, one-way, and not orchestrator-mediated. Cron and webhook triggers run directly against the selected project.
- Keep the Channels vs Triggers split. Do not route webhook traffic through the orchestrator.
- The orchestrator is not a long-lived provider subprocess. It performs one CLI print-mode run per incoming message and persists provider-qualified session ids in `orchestrator.channelSessions`.
- `hub-mcp` is a separate stdio MCP server. It delegates to the hub HTTP API so the hub remains the single writer.
- Pipelines (`@claude-hub/pipeline`) drive per-project assembly lines: work items flow through the fixed stages intake → spec → code → test → deploy → monitor. Stage execution goes through `agent-runner` (plus generic shell commands for test/deploy/monitor); one item runs per project at a time; per-stage gates (`auto`/`approval`) control autonomy. Intake paths: manual REST, triggers with `mode: 'enqueue'` (bridged via a callback in `main.ts` — never a triggers→pipeline dependency), and the `enqueue_work_request` hub-mcp tool for channels. Monitor failures auto-file defect work items (loop-guarded for monitor-sourced items).
- Claude MCP uses the generated `--mcp-config` path. Cursor MCP is scoped to the orchestrator workdir through `.cursor/mcp.json`.
- Cross-cutting shared types belong in `packages/core/src/types.ts`. Avoid package cycles.
